=========================================
GENERIC LAMBDAS (C++14) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is a Generic Lambda?
----------------------------
- Generic lambda is a C++14 feature.
- It allows lambda parameters to use "auto".
- This makes the lambda work with multiple data types.
- Also called "polymorphic lambda".

-----------------------------------------

2. Syntax
---------
auto lambdaName = [](auto param) {
    // logic
};

-----------------------------------------

3. Basic Example
----------------
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {

    auto print = [](auto x) {
        cout << x << endl;
    };

    print(10);        // int
    print(3.14);      // double
    print("Hello");   // string

    return 0;
}

-----------------------------------------

4. Why Generic Lambdas are Needed?
-----------------------------------
Before C++14:
- Lambda needed fixed parameter types

Example (C++11 limitation):
[](int x) { ... }  // only int

Problem:
- Needed multiple overloads or templates

Solution:
- Generic lambda removes duplication

-----------------------------------------

5. How it works internally
--------------------------
- Compiler treats it like a templated call operator:

Equivalent concept:

struct Lambda {
    template <typename T>
    void operator()(T x) const {
        cout << x;
    }
};

-----------------------------------------

6. Multiple Parameters
----------------------

auto add = [](auto a, auto b) {
    return a + b;
};

cout << add(10, 20);
cout << add(2.5, 3.5);

-----------------------------------------

7. Mix with STL (VERY IMPORTANT)
-------------------------------

#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};

for_each(v.begin(), v.end(), [](auto &x) {
    x = x * 2;
});

-----------------------------------------

8. Generic Lambda with Reference
-------------------------------

auto modify = [](auto &x) {
    x += 10;
};

int a = 5;
modify(a);  // a becomes 15

-----------------------------------------

9. Capture + Generic Lambda
--------------------------

int factor = 2;

auto multiply = [factor](auto x) {
    return x * factor;
};

cout << multiply(10);    // 20
cout << multiply(2.5);   // 5.0

-----------------------------------------

10. Limitations
--------------
- Cannot partially specialize lambdas
- Complex templates inside lambda may reduce readability
- Overuse can make code unclear

-----------------------------------------

11. When to use?
---------------
- STL algorithms (for_each, transform, sort)
- Generic utilities
- Callback functions
- Quick reusable logic

-----------------------------------------

12. Interview Key Points
------------------------
- Introduced in C++14
- Uses "auto" in lambda parameters
- Equivalent to templated function operator()
- Works with any data type
- Commonly used with STL algorithms

